Re: the government deployment, there is no way on God=E2=80=99s green earth=
 that
the product will be approved for use on anything except government
infrastructure, which for this customer means C2S, the classified AWS
cloud. C2S has, to put it mildly, some quirks. But a relatively simple
system shouldn=E2=80=99t run into technical limitations on core services.

To get this done, you=E2=80=99ll need a pro services partner that is alread=
y
on-site and cleared to deploy software. You=E2=80=99ll need some basic soft=
ware
assurance running continuously (i.e. live state knowledge on codebase
vulnerabilities), which Ion Channel can provide. You could also benefit
from deployment into a C2S emulator, which Sequoia Combine runs, so that
when you deploy the system into a copy of C2S you can see the little places
where it breaks (mostly because it=E2=80=99s calling out to the Internet, w=
hich
isn=E2=80=99t possible on C2S) - that saves time and cost, because it elimi=
nates
(most of) the telephone game of tickets about why something=E2=80=99s not w=
orking
on a network you don=E2=80=99t have access to. All of this can (and should)=
 be
priced into your proposal.

Nothing that touches agency personnel, anonymized or not, will ever run on
commercial SaaS. Given that, your folks need to do cost-benefit on whether
it=E2=80=99s worth winning this opportunity. I can make the intro to the de=
ployment
